  <h1>Pedestrian Accident Fault and Comparative Negligence</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Pure comparative fault</h2><p>California, New York, Florida, and 10 other states. The pedestrian can recover even if 99% at fault — damages are simply reduced by the pedestrian&rsquo;s percentage. A pedestrian 50% at fault recovers 50% of total damages.</p>
  <h2>Modified comparative fault</h2><p>Most states (approximately 33). Recovery is barred if the pedestrian is 50% or more at fault (the &ldquo;50% bar&rdquo; rule) or 51% or more (the &ldquo;51% bar&rdquo; rule). Below the threshold, damages are reduced proportionally.</p>
  <h2>Contributory negligence</h2><p>Alabama, DC, Maryland, North Carolina, and Virginia. Any fault by the pedestrian — even 1% — bars recovery entirely. This rule is harsh and increasingly rare. Some of these states recognize the &ldquo;last clear chance&rdquo; doctrine as an exception: if the driver had the last opportunity to avoid the accident and failed, the pedestrian may recover despite their own negligence.</p>
  <h2>Jaywalking and fault</h2><p>Crossing outside a crosswalk doesn&rsquo;t automatically make the pedestrian 50% at fault. Courts look at the totality: was the pedestrian clearly visible? Was the driver speeding? Was the driver distracted? Jaywalking is a factor, not a bar to recovery in comparative fault states.</p>
